WorldStage Newsonline—-In a bid to prevent artificial scarcity of petroleum products in Ekiti State, the State’s Government has warned owners and operators of filling stations in the state to desist from hoarding of the products or face the consequences. The government’s warning was contained in a statement issued by the Chief Press Secretary to the Governor, Mr Olayinka Oyebode  in Ado Ekiti. Oyebode said that such an act was fast creating artificial fuel scarcity in the state. He noted that hoarding of petroleum products was an act of economic sabotage, which created unnecessary hardship for the people and cripples businesses. Oyebode said that monitoring teams had been despatched to go round filling stations in the state and ensure that no filling station hoard fuel at the detriment of the people. “Any filling station caught hoarding fuel will receive heavy sanction,’’ he said. According to him, the state Governor, Dr Kayode Fayemi has urged the citizens of the state not to panic but go about their normal business activities peacefully and responsibly. Fuel scarcity became noticeable in Ado Ekiti, the state capital and other major towns like Ikere, Ijero, Ikole, Aramoko and Ifaki Ekiti among others since Thursday. The development had led to the return of long queues in few filling stations that were dispensing the products, while many of them had locked their gates.